{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is real watcher recursion over live filesystem events (REAL-INFRA). A mocked watcher can hide platform/library watch-scope bugs (MOCK-HIDE).","test_description":"Start the real daemon against a temp watched root on disk, create `root/subdir/input.txt`, and assert transformed output appears in the output directory without restart. Run on target OS/filesystem in CI to catch real watch-recursion failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.28,"System":0.64,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is primarily path+time-window decision logic inside dedup state handling (MOCK-MISS says single-object logic). No real OS/network/subprocess is required.","test_description":"Instantiate dedup component with a fixed clock, submit same path twice within window, assert second is rejected; advance clock past window and assert next request is accepted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on real OS event burst patterns (REAL-INFRA). Synthetic single-event mocks can miss duplicate event sequences produced by actual watchers (MOCK-HIDE).","test_description":"Run daemon with real watcher, perform a single write pattern known to trigger multiple event